That&#39;s not what enums are for.

Enums represent a __type__ (such as, say, &#39;Tree&#39;, or &#39;Recipe&#39;) that has the following properties:

* It is final - there is no need to subclass it. You won&#39;t be needing, say, &#39;VegetarianRecipe&#39; or &#39;DeciduousTree&#39;. In other words, the &#39;members&#39; of the type do not need to change for specific species of this type (i.e. if DeciduousTree needs to have a `getLeafFallMonth()` method but non-deciduous trees shouldn&#39;t have that method at all, there is a difference in what members are exposed for different species. In which case, __enums are not appropriate__).

* There are a limited number of instances that can ever exist for this type, and they can __all__ be fully and entirely specified at code-write time by the author who made that type. If, for example, it is possible to add recipes (in addition to, say, a bunch of common recipes that the app ships out of the box), then __enums are not appropriate__.

If the above accurately describes recipes, then `Recipe` _itself_ needs to be the enum:

```
public enum Recipe {
  LASAGNA(&quot;LASAGNA&quot;, 35, true, &quot;Meat, Cheese, Onions, Garlic, Noodles&quot;),
  PIZZA(....),
  ;

  Recipe(String code, int price, boolean containsMeaet, String ingredients) {
  ....
}
}
```

is how to do it. If either one doesn&#39;t apply, then _do not use enum at all_, that&#39;s not what they are for. You would, presumably, want exposed constants. Looks like:

```
public Recipe {
  public Recipe(String code, int price, boolean containsMeaet, String ingredients)
  { ....}

  public static final Recipe LASAGNA = new Recipe(&quot;LASAGNA&quot;, 35, ...);
}
```

There is no need for `PopularRecipes`. If you really want it, it would be a class whose only purpose is as a container for `public static final Recipe LASAGNA` and other popular recipes. To ensure nobody tries something silly, like instantiate a new instance of PopularRecipes, add a constructor, make it `private`.

I believe you may just be misunderstanding the error.

```none
The method addRecipe(Recipe) in the type Recipes is not applicable for the arguments (PopularRecipes)
```

This is because the _addRecipe_ method has a _Recipe_ parameter type, and not a _PopularRecipes_ type.

The solution is to create a method within _PopularRecipes_, to return the _Recipe_ value.

```java
public enum PopularRecipes{
    LASAGNA (new Recipe(&quot;LASAGNA&quot;, 35, true, &quot;Meat, Cheese, Onions, Garlic, Noodles&quot;));

    private Recipe recipe;

    PopularRecipes(Recipe recipe) {
        this.recipe = recipe;
    }

    public Recipe getRecipe() {
        return recipe;
    }
}
```

Then, you can apply the method call, to your _addRecipe_ argument.

```java
private final Recipes PAGE_ONE = new Recipes().addRecipe(PopularRecipes.LASAGNA.getRecipe())
```

As an alternative, you can have the _addRecipe_ method do the parsing.  
So, you can still offer just the _enum_ value.

```java
public Recipes addRecipe(PopularRecipes popularRecipes) {
    Recipe recipe = popularRecipes.getRecipe();
    
}
```

&gt; _&quot;... I feel like I&#39;m misunderstanding something critical about enums ...&quot;_

There are many applications for _enum_ sets, and not necessarily one way to abstract it.

What you&#39;re using is fine, although, there is a better way to organize this data.

Consider the following examples.

Since you are utilizing the recipe name in more than one form, create an _enum_ for it.  
I&#39;ll add a new _Recipe_, also, to convey the example.

```java
enum RecipeName {
    Lasagna, BakedZiti
}
```

Additionally, since an ingredient can be used in many different recipes, create an _enum_ for this as well.  
This will remove any possible bugs that can arrive from typographical errors, common with manually entered text values&amp;mdash;especially when you are typing the same value, repeatedly.

```java
enum Ingredient {
    Meat, Cheese, Onions, Garlic, Noodles,
    Ziti, TomatoSauce
}
```

Now, your _Recipe_ class can utilize both of these.  
As a note, I was unsure what your _boolean_ value was, so I just named it _&quot;value&quot;_.

```java
class Recipe {
    RecipeName name;
    String price;
    boolean value;
    List&lt;Ingredient&gt; ingredients = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    Recipe(RecipeName name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void setPrice(String price) {
        this.price = price;
    }

    void setValue(boolean value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    void addIngredients(Ingredient... ingredients) {
        this.ingredients.addAll(List.of(ingredients));
    }
}
```

Additionally, your _PopularRecipes_ class can be a static structure.  
And, since I&#39;m re-using both _RecipeName_ and _Ingredient_ multiple times, I&#39;ve added them as static imports.

```java
import static Ingredient.*;
import static RecipeName.*;
```

```java
class PopularRecipes {
    static List&lt;Recipe&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    static {
        Recipe lasagna = new Recipe(Lasagna);
        lasagna.setPrice(&quot;35&quot;);
        lasagna.setValue(true);
        lasagna.addIngredients(Meat, Cheese, Onions, Garlic, Noodles);
        list.add(lasagna);

        Recipe bakedZiti = new Recipe(BakedZiti);
        bakedZiti.setPrice(&quot;20&quot;);
        bakedZiti.addIngredients(Ziti, Cheese, TomatoSauce, Garlic);
        list.add(bakedZiti);
    }

    /** @return null if not found */
    static Recipe getRecipe(RecipeName recipeName) {
        for (Recipe recipe : list) {
            if (recipe.name == recipeName) return recipe;
        }
        return null;
    }
}
```

Organizing the data in this fashion improves scalability, for appending a collection of recipes.

There are numerous ways to contain the data, this is just an example.

